{"title_page": "A. E. Kinnear", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian public servant}}\n[[File:A portrait of A E Kinnear - Secretary to the Public Service Commissioner(GN02128).jpg|thumb|A. E. Kinnear - Secretary to the Public Service Commissioner, c.a. 1905]]\n\n'''A. E. Kinnear''' was Secretary to the Public Service Commissioner in South Australia.\n\n== Career ==\nMr. Kinnear entered the [[Crown_land#Australia|Crown Lands Department]] as junior clerk on December 11, 1882, made rapid progress in various departments. He was appointed secretary of the Public Service Classification Board in 1901 and acted in that capacity until the completion of the work of the board. He was appointed accountant in the Surveyor-General's Department in 1902, and the position of accountant to the Advances to Settlers' Board was added in 1909. For the next two years he was organising secretary of the egg production and marketing scheme for the Produce Department. In 1911 he returned to the Survey Department as accountant.<ref name=\"Advertiser\">[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/35032267 ''Fifty years in service.''] The Advertiser, Adelaide, South Australia, Wednesday 16 January 1935. Page 22.</ref>\n\nIn 1917, Mr. Kinnear became secretary to the first [[Public Service Commission]]er, and a few months later also became secretary of the Public Service Reclassification Board. He has acted as Deputy Public Service Commissioner on many occasions.<ref name=\"Advertiser\"/>\n\n== References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Public servants of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Crown land]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:A portrait of A E Kinnear - Secretary to the Public Service Commissioner(GN02128).jpg|thumb|A. E. Kinnear - Secretary to the Public Service Commissioner, c.a. 1905]]\n\n'''A. E. Kinnear''' was Secretary to the Public Service Commissioner in South Australia.\n\n== Career ==\nMr. Kinnear entered the [[Crown_land#Australia|Crown Lands Department]] as junior clerk on December 11, 1882, made rapid progress in various departments. He was appointed secretary of the Public Service Classification Board in 1901 and acted in that capacity until the completion of the work of the board. He was appointed accountant in the Surveyor-General's Department in 1902, and the position of accountant to the Advances to Settlers' Board was added in 1909. For the next two years he was organising secretary of the egg production and marketing scheme for the Produce Department. In 1911 he returned to the Survey Department as accountant.<ref name=\"Advertiser\">[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/35032267 ''Fifty years in service.''] The Advertiser, Adelaide, South Australia, Wednesday 16 January 1935. Page 22.</ref>\n\nIn 1917, Mr. Kinnear became secretary to the first [[Public Service Commission]]er, and a few months later also became secretary of the Public Service Reclassification Board. He has acted as Deputy Public Service Commissioner on many occasions.<ref name=\"Advertiser\"/>\n\n== References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Public servants of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Crown land]]\n", "name_user": "Saga City", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"Australian public servant\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A._E._Kinnear"}
{"title_page": "Ian McColl (journalist)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n'''Ian McColl''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (22 February 1915 \u2013 21 June 2005), was a Scottish journalist, editor and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician.\n\n==Background==\nHe was the eldest son of John McColl and Sarah Isabella (aka Morag) McPherson, of [[Glasgow]] and [[Bunessan]], [[Isle of Mull]]. He was educated at [[Hillhead High School]], Glasgow. He married, in 1968, Brenda McKean. They had one daughter. He served during the war, with the [[Royal Air Force]], 1940\u201346 (despatches, 1945). He was with Air Crew, Coastal Command [[No. 202 Squadron RAF|202 Squadron]].<ref>\u2018McCOLL, Ian\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132007; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2012 ; online edn, Nov 2012 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U25403, accessed 29 Nov 2013]</ref>\nhttps://mullfamilies.co.uk//getperson.php?personID=I22619&tree=MF\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1931 he joined the Liberal Party at the age of 16. In 1933 he was elected to the executive of the Scottish Liberal Federation. In 1938 he became Honorary Secretary of the Scottish Liberal Federation.<ref>The Times House of Commons, 1950</ref> McColl twice stood as a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal party]] candidate for the United Kingdom Parliament; in the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 General Election]] at [[Dumfriesshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Dumfriesshire]] finishing third \n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1945 United Kingdom general election|General Election 1945]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/edates.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216152334/http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/edates.htm |archive-date=16 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nElectorate  47,983\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)\n|candidate  = [[Niall Macpherson, 1st Baron Drumalbyn|Niall Malcolm Stewart Macpherson]]\n|votes  = 16,465\n|percentage  = 47.4\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = D Dunwoodie\n|votes  = 12,388\n|percentage  = 35.7\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  =  '''Fl-Off. Ian McColl'''\n|votes  = 5,850\n|percentage  = 16.9\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 4,077\n|percentage  = 11.7\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = \n|percentage  = 72.3\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nand at the [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950 General Election]] at [[Greenock (UK Parliament constituency)|Greenock]] coming second.\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1950 United Kingdom general election|General Election 1950]]\nElectorate  48,792\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Hector McNeil]]\n|votes  = 20,548\n|percentage  = 50.6\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  =  '''Ian McColl'''\n|votes  = 11,638\n|percentage  = 28.7\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Independent Labour\n|candidate  =  J. S. Thomson\n|votes  = 6,458\n|percentage  = 15.9\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Communist Party of Great Britain\n|candidate  = [[John Ross Campbell]]\n|votes  = 1,228\n|percentage  = 3.0\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n|party      = Irish Anti-Partitionist\n|candidate  = O. Brown\n|votes  = 718\n|percentage  = 1.8\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 8,910\n|percentage  = 21.9\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = \n|percentage  = 83.2\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box win\n  |winner     = Labour Party (UK)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Media career==\nHe joined the [[Scottish Daily Express]] as a cub reporter in 1933. He was Editor of the Scottish Daily Express from 1961\u201371. He was Editor of the [[Daily Express]] from 1971\u201374.<ref>{{cite web|title=Editors of the Daily Express|url=http://www.dailydrone.co.uk/express-editors.html|publisher=\"Daily Drone\"|accessdate=18 May 2012}}</ref> He was a Director of Express Newspapers Ltd, from 1971\u201382. He was Chairman of Scottish Express Newspapers Ltd, from 1975\u201382. He was a Member of the [[Press Council (UK)|Press Council]] from 1975\u201378. He was a Vice-President of the Newspaper Press Fund from 1981\u20132005. He was Chairman of the Media Division for the [[1986 Commonwealth Games]], Scotland from 1983\u201386. He was honoured with the Bank of Scotland, Scottish Press Life Achievement Award, in 1993.\n\nHe was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire]] in 1983.\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{Succession box| before=[[Derek Marks]]|title=Editor of ''[[Daily Express|The Daily Express]]''|years=1971 - October 1974|after=[[Alastair Burnet]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Daily Express editors}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McColl, Ian}}\n[[Category:Daily Express people]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Party parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n'''Ian McColl''' [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (22 February 1915 \u2013 21 June 2005), was a Scottish journalist, editor and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician.\n\n==Background==\nHe was the eldest son of John McColl and Sarah Isabella (aka Morag) McPherson, of [[Glasgow]] and [[Bunessan]], [[Isle of Mull]]. He was educated at [[Hillhead High School]], Glasgow. He married, in 1968, Brenda McKean. They had one daughter. He served during the war, with the [[Royal Air Force]], 1940\u201346 (despatches, 1945). He was with Air Crew, Coastal Command [[No. 202 Squadron RAF|202 Squadron]].<ref>\u2018McCOLL, Ian\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132007; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2012 ; online edn, Nov 2012 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U25403, accessed 29 Nov 2013]</ref>\nhttps://mullfamilies.co.uk//getperson.php?personID=I22619&tree=MF\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1931 he joined the Liberal Party at the age of 16. In 1933 he was elected to the executive of the Scottish Liberal Federation. In 1938 he became Honorary Secretary of the Scottish Liberal Federation.<ref>The Times House of Commons, 1950</ref> McColl twice stood as a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal party]] candidate for the United Kingdom Parliament; in the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 General Election]] at [[Dumfriesshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Dumfriesshire]] finishing third \n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1945 United Kingdom general election|General Election 1945]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/edates.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216152334/http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/edates.htm |archive-date=16 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nElectorate  47,983\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)\n|candidate  = [[Niall Macpherson, 1st Baron Drumalbyn|Niall Malcolm Stewart Macpherson]]\n|votes  = 16,465\n|percentage  = 47.4\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = D Dunwoodie\n|votes  = 12,388\n|percentage  = 35.7\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  =  '''Fl-Off. Ian McColl'''\n|votes  = 5,850\n|percentage  = 16.9\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 4,077\n|percentage  = 11.7\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = \n|percentage  = 72.3\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nand at the [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950 General Election]] at [[Greenock (UK Parliament constituency)|Greenock]] coming second.\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1950 United Kingdom general election|General Election 1950]]\nElectorate  48,792\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Hector McNeil]]\n|votes  = 20,548\n|percentage  = 50.6\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  =  '''Ian McColl'''\n|votes  = 11,638\n|percentage  = 28.7\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Independent Labour\n|candidate  =  J. S. Thomson\n|votes  = 6,458\n|percentage  = 15.9\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Communist Party of Great Britain\n|candidate  = [[John Ross Campbell]]\n|votes  = 1,228\n|percentage  = 3.0\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate\n|party      = Irish Anti-Partitionist\n|candidate  = O. Brown\n|votes  = 718\n|percentage  = 1.8\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 8,910\n|percentage  = 21.9\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = \n|percentage  = 83.2\n|change  = \n}}\n{{Election box win\n  |winner     = Labour Party (UK)\n  |swing      = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Media career==\nHe joined the [[Scottish Daily Express]] as a cub reporter in 1933. He was Editor of the Scottish Daily Express from 1961\u201371. He was Editor of the [[Daily Express]] from 1971\u201374.<ref>{{cite web|title=Editors of the Daily Express|url=http://www.dailydrone.co.uk/express-editors.html|publisher=\"Daily Drone\"|accessdate=18 May 2012}}</ref> He was a Director of Express Newspapers Ltd, from 1971\u201382. He was Chairman of Scottish Express Newspapers Ltd, from 1975\u201382. He was a Member of the [[Press Council (UK)|Press Council]] from 1975\u201378. He was a Vice-President of the Newspaper Press Fund from 1981\u20132005. He was Chairman of the Media Division for the [[1986 Commonwealth Games]], Scotland from 1983\u201386. He was honoured with the Bank of Scotland, Scottish Press Life Achievement Award, in 1993.\n\nHe was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire]] in 1983.\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{Succession box| before=[[Derek Marks]]|title=Editor of ''[[Daily Express|The Daily Express]]''|years=1971 - October 1974|after=[[Alastair Burnet]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Daily Express editors}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McColl, Ian}}\n[[Category:Daily Express people]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Party parliamentary candidates]]\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ian_McColl_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "Harry S. Truman Scholarship", "text_new": "[[File:Harry S Truman, bw half-length photo portrait, facing front, 1945.jpg|right|thumb|President [[Harry S. Truman]]]]\n\nThe '''Harry S. Truman Scholarship''' is the premier graduate fellowship in the United States for public service leadership.<ref>https://www.truman.gov/our-mission/who-we-are</ref> A federally funded [[scholarship]] granted to U.S. undergraduate students for demonstrated leadership potential, academic excellence, and a commitment to public service, the Harry S. Truman Scholarship is the most highly competitive American fellowship to support graduate education and leadership development.<ref>https://www.truman.gov/</ref> It is administered by the Harry S. Truman Scholarship Foundation, an independent federal agency based in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n[[United States Congress|Congress]] created the scholarship in 1975 as a living [[memorial]] to [[Harry S. Truman|the 33rd president of the United States]]. Instead of a statue, the Truman Scholarship is the official federal memorial to its namesake president. According to the ''[[Washington Post]]'', the Truman Scholarship's \"sole aim is to pick out people with potential to become leaders\u2014then provide support to help them realize their aspirations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/27/AR2006082700747.html|title=Present Scholars, Future Leaders|first=Anushka|last=Asthana|date=28 August 2006|publisher=|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref> The scholarship supports public service oriented graduate study in the amount of $30,000.\n\nEach year, between 50 and 60 university nominated candidates in their junior year are named Truman Scholars following a rigorous application process involving essays, recommendations, and an interview.<ref name=\"truman.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.truman.gov/candidates/faq-candidates/|title=FAQ \u2013 Candidates \u2013 The Harry S. Truman Scholarship Foundation|publisher=}}</ref> Scholarships have historically been awarded to one individual from each U.S. state.<ref>https://www.truman.gov/candidates/how-become-truman-scholar</ref> Each university in the United States may only nominate four candidates annually, who represent the most accomplished nominees from that university.<ref>https://www.truman.gov/candidates/how-become-truman-scholar</ref> \n\nToday, Truman Scholars are represented at the highest levels of U.S. public service. \n\n== History ==\nOn May 30, 1974, Senator [[Stuart Symington]] of [[Missouri]] sponsored S.3548,<ref>[https://www.congress.gov/bill/93rd-congress/senate-bill/3548 S.3548]</ref> formally titled \"A bill to establish the Harry S Truman Memorial Scholarships.\" Symington held the same [[List of United States Senators from Missouri|Class 1 Senate seat]] that Truman had held from 1935\u20131945 before becoming [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]. The [[United States Senate|Senate]] passed the bill on August 2, and the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] followed suit on December 17. Two similar House bills, H.R.15138<ref>[https://www.congress.gov/bill/93rd-congress/house-bill/15138 H.R.15138]</ref> sponsored by [[William J. Randall]] of [[Missouri]] and H.R.17481<ref>[https://www.congress.gov/bill/93rd-congress/house-bill/17481 H.R.17481]</ref> sponsored by [[James G. O'Hara]] of [[Michigan]], were set aside in favor of Symington's bill.\n\nThe bill was signed by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Gerald Ford]] and enacted as Public Law 93-642 on January 4, 1975 and entered the [[United States Statutes at Large]] as 88 Stat. 2276\u20132280, and the [[United States Code]] as 20 U.S.C. 2001\u20132013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/html/uscode20/usc_sup_01_20_10_42.html|title=20 U.S. Code Chapter 42 \u2013 HARRY S TRUMAN MEMORIAL SCHOLARSHIPS|publisher=}}</ref> It now operates as Program 85.001, governed by 45 CFR 1801<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.access.gpo.gov/nara/cfr/waisidx_04/45cfr1801_04.html|title=Public Welfare|publisher=|access-date=2006-07-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928173137/http://www.access.gpo.gov/nara/cfr/waisidx_04/45cfr1801_04.html|archive-date=2006-09-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> as published in the [[Code of Federal Regulations]] in the [[Federal Register]].\n\n== Governance ==\n[[File:Truman Foundation logo.jpg|thumb|Harry S. Truman Scholarship Foundation]]\nThe Truman Scholarship is administered by the Harry S Truman Scholarship Foundation, an independent federal executive branch agency. It is governed by a 13-member Board of Trustees headed by President [[Madeleine Albright]], who says the foundation \"serves as a gateway for America's public service leaders\" and \"does a remarkable job of identifying future change agents.\" <ref>[http://www.truman.gov/about/about_list.htm?cat_id=467 Truman Scholarship Foundation members] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060710182014/http://www.truman.gov/about/about_list.htm?cat_id=467 |date=2006-07-10 }}</ref> The Foundation's operations<ref>https://www.truman.gov/officers-board-trustees</ref> are overseen by full-time Executive Secretary [[Terry Babcock-Lumish]].  Its endowment, which takes the form of a federal trust fund held in the [[U.S. Department of the Treasury]], is $55 million. Current Board members include Senator [[Roy Blunt]], Senator [[Brian Schatz]], Secretary of Education [[Betsy DeVos]], Congressman [[Kay Granger]], and Congressman [[Ted Deutch]].\n\n== Qualifications ==\nThe scholarship is awarded to between 50 and 60 U.S. college juniors each year on the basis of four criteria:<ref>[http://www.truman.gov/faq/faq_show.htm?doc_id=249095 Primary selection criteria for scholarship] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924030815/http://www.truman.gov/faq/faq_show.htm?doc_id=249095 |date=2006-09-24 }}</ref> service on campus and in the community, commitment to a career in public service (government, uniformed services, research, education, or public interest/advocacy organizations), communication ability and aptitude to be a \"change agent,\" and academic talent that would assure acceptance to a first-rate graduate school.  More broadly, Truman Scholars possess intellect, leadership skills, and passion that would make them a likely force for the public good in any field.<ref>[http://www.truman.gov/faq/faq_show.htm?doc_id=246879 Who are Truman Scholars?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924030913/http://www.truman.gov/faq/faq_show.htm?doc_id=246879 |date=2006-09-24 }}</ref>\n\n== Application process ==\nIn order to apply for the scholarship, students must first win the nomination of their undergraduate university. Each undergraduate institution in the United States is allowed to nominate up to four students who have attended since freshman year. After nomination, annually the Foundation receives 900 applications, of whom between 50 and 60 will be selected each year.<ref name=\"truman.gov\" /> Each nominated application is then examined by a regional review panel, which selects finalists to interview. The interviews are conducted by panels of former Truman scholars, trustees of the board, and notable national public servants. These panelists then make final selections of scholarship winners, generally attempting to choose one from each of the 50 states and American territories. No particular career, service interest, or policy field is preferred during the process.  Each year, the Truman Scholarship is awarded to one or two students from institutions that have never had a Truman Scholar.<ref>[http://www.truman.gov/faq/faq_show.htm?doc_id=249198 There has never been a Truman Scholar from my school. Do I have a chance?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924030632/http://www.truman.gov/faq/faq_show.htm?doc_id=249198 |date=2006-09-24 }}</ref>\n\n== Benefits ==\n[[File:TSA LOGO.jpg|thumb|150px|Truman Scholars Association]]\nScholars currently receive an award of $30,000 going toward up to three years of graduate education leading to a career in the public service.<ref>[http://www.truman.gov/faq/faq_show.htm?doc_id=244611 What benefits do Truman Scholars receive?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924031037/http://www.truman.gov/faq/faq_show.htm?doc_id=244611 |date=2006-09-24 }}</ref> Winners also benefit from a network of other scholars through the [http://www.trumanscholars.org/ Truman Scholars Association] and lasting friendship, which is encouraged by the Truman Scholars Leadership Week at [[William Jewell College]] in [[Liberty, Missouri]], and the [[Harry S. Truman Presidential Library and Museum|Truman Library]] in [[Independence, Missouri]], during which new scholars collaborate on policy projects. Scholars accept a 10-week Summer Institute internship in [[Washington, D.C.]], which features additional professional development training. Of this group, a small number continue federal agency jobs for a full year as part of the Truman Albright Fellows program.\n\nCertain graduate and professional schools, including the Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs, give some degree of priority and funding to applicants who are Truman Scholars. Truman Scholars are exempt from taking the written section of the [[United States Foreign Service|U.S. Foreign Service Exam]]. Scholars also automatically become part of the [[Truman Scholars Association]], independent  non-profit that works to foster additional opportunities and networking for Scholars.\n\n== Notable Truman Scholars ==\n{{see also|Category:Truman Scholars}}\n\n=== 1970s ===\n* Ernest Calder\u00f3n (1977), Member of the [[Arizona Board of Regents]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www4.nau.edu/insidenau/bumps/4_20_05/calderon.htm|title=Welcome to NAU \u2013 NAU News  : NAU News|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Janet Napolitano]] (1977), [[Governor of Arizona]], 2003\u20132009, Secretary of [[Department of Homeland Security|Homeland Security]] under President [[Barack Obama]] (2009\u20132013), President of the [[University of California]] (2013\u2013present)\n* Frederick G. Slabach (1977), [[Texas Wesleyan University]] President, Dean Emeritus and Professor of Law,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://law.txwes.edu/Faculty/FacultyProfiles/FrederickGSlabach/tabid/841/Default.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-12-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326140519/http://www.law.txwes.edu/Faculty/FacultyProfiles/FrederickGSlabach/tabid/841/Default.aspx |archivedate=2012-03-26 }}</ref> Former Executive Secretary of the Truman Scholarship Foundation\n* Dwight Dively (1978), Director of Finance for the City of [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://cascadecourses.org/facstaff/bios/Dively.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-07-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060508042651/http://cascadecourses.org/facstaff/bios/Dively.html |archivedate=2006-05-08 }}</ref>\n* Awilda R. Marquez (1978), Director of the Department of Excise and Licenses, [[Denver, Colorado]]\n* Keith B. Richburg (1978), Author and correspondent for the ''[[Washington Post]]'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keithrichburg.com/|title=Keith B. Richburg \u2013 International reporting on China \u2013 Asia \u2013 Africa \u2013 Europe|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Robert J. Van Der Velde (1979), Dean, [[Napa Valley College]]\n\n=== 1980s ===\n*[[Stephen Censky]] (1980), [[United States Deputy Secretary of Agriculture]].\n* [[Jeffrey Toobin]] (1980), senior legal analyst for [[CNN]] and staff writer at ''[[The New Yorker]]''\n* David Adkins (1981), Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Kansas]] Medical Center; Executive Director of the Council of State Governments\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Bouchard (Judge)|Andr\u00e9 Bouchard]] (1981), Chancellor of the [[Delaware Court of Chancery]]<ref name=\"Jaan_Bouchard\">{{cite news|title=Delaware Governor Nominates Law Firm Chief to Head Court of Chancery|url= http://www.jdjournal.com/2014/03/21/delaware-governor-nominates-law-firm-chief-to-head-court-of-chancery/|agency=JD Journal|publisher=JDJOURNAL|date=21 Mar 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Bill de Blasio]] (1981), New York City Mayor\n* [[Bill Halter]] (1981), former Lieutenant Governor of Arkansas and U.S. Senate candidate\n* [[George Stephanopoulos]] (1981), former political adviser to [[Bill Clinton]], current Chief Anchor for [[ABC News]]\n* David Cooley (1982), Deputy Governor of [[Tennessee]]\n* Matt Crowl (1982), Deputy Chief of Staff to the [[Richard M. Daley|Mayor of Chicago]]\n* Leslie Koch (1982), President of the [[Governors Island]] Preservation and Education Corporation <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govisland.com/Press_Room/04-04-06koch.asp|title=Governors Island|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060621200729/http://www.govisland.com/Press_Room/04-04-06koch.asp|archivedate=2006-06-21}}</ref>\n* Laurel McFarland (1982), Executive Director, National Association of Schools of Public Affairs and Administration <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naspaa.org/about_naspaa/staff/staff.asp|title=NASPAA *The Global Standard in Public Service Education*|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Andra Samoa]] (1982), CEO of [[American Samoa]] Power Authority <ref>[http://www.pacificislands.cc/pina/pinadefault2.php?urlpinaid=23298 Pacific Magazine: AMERICAN SAMOA: New Power Authority CEO Controversial Selection<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Thomas Sugrue]] (1982), professor of history and sociology at [[New York University]]\n* [[G. Murray Snow]] (1982), federal judge for the [[United States District Court for the District of Arizona]].<ref>https://www.truman.gov/phoenix-arizona</ref> \n* [[Chris Coons]] (1983), U.S. Senator for [[Delaware]]\n* [[Russ Dallen]] (1983), Editor-in-chief of the [[Latin American Herald Tribune]], and previously the [http://www